<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-03-30T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-03-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="254" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d254">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72112/989½</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-03-30">
                                    <hi rend="italic">30 March, 1915</hi>.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: This note<note n="71" xml:id="d254fn1">For text of the note as sent, see <ref target="frus1915Supp#pg_152">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1915, supp., p.
                                    152</ref>.</note> is entirely satisfactory to me with the
                            alterations you have suggested, and I entirely approve of adding the
                            paragraph you have drawn as the concluding passage of the note.</p>
                        <p>I hope that the encyphering and all the handling of this note will be
                            under the safeguards as to privacy which we agreed upon, so that there
                            may be no garbled versions of it current before it reaches London. I
                            assume that it will be agreed between Washington and London that it will
                            be published here upon its receipt and delivery there.</p>
                        <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>W. W.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>